# Write your code to answer exercise 2a here

library(tidyverse)

strava_runs <- read_csv("data/strava_runs.csv")
## Rows: 40471 Columns: 7
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (2): gender, timestamp
## dbl (5): athlete, distance..m., elapsed.time..s., elevation.gain..m., averag...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
data_5k_10k <- strava_runs %>%
  mutate(
    event = case_when(
      `distance..m.` > 4998 & `distance..m.` < 5015  ~ "5k",
      `distance..m.` > 9998 & `distance..m.` < 10015 ~ "10k",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    )
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(event))

data_5k_10k <- data_5k_10k %>%
  mutate(
    pace = `elapsed.time..s.` / 60 / (`distance..m.` / 1000)
  )

ggplot(data = data_5k_10k, aes(x = event, y = pace)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "skyblue", color = "darkblue", alpha = 0.6) +
  facet_wrap(~ gender) +
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Running Pace for 5K and 10K Runs by Gender",
    subtitle = "Pace measured in minutes per kilometer",
    x = "Run Type",
    y = "Pace (min/km)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    strip.text = element_text(face = "bold"),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold")
  )

#Write your text to answer exercise 2b here (Please delete this message before submission!)_
#Runners generally have faster paces in 5K runs compared to 10K runs, and male runners tend to have slightly faster median paces than female runners. Additionally, pace variation is larger in 10K runs, indicating more differences in endurance over longer distances.

# Write your code to answer exercise 3 here

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(readr)

strava_runs <- read_csv("data/strava_runs.csv")
## Rows: 40471 Columns: 7
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (2): gender, timestamp
## dbl (5): athlete, distance..m., elapsed.time..s., elevation.gain..m., averag...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
possible_time_cols <- c("elapsed.time..s.", "elapsed_time", "moving_time", "duration", "total_elapsed_time", "time")
time_col <- NULL

for (col in possible_time_cols) {
  if (col %in% names(strava_runs)) {
    time_col <- col
    break
  }
}

if (is.null(time_col)) {
  
  numeric_cols <- names(strava_runs)[sapply(strava_runs, is.numeric)]
  print("Available numeric columns (potential time columns):")
  print(numeric_cols)
  stop("Please identify which column contains elapsed time in seconds from the list above.")
} else {
  print(paste("Using time column:", time_col))
}
## [1] "Using time column: elapsed.time..s."
runner_avg_distance <- strava_runs %>%
  group_by(athlete) %>%
  summarise(avg_distance_km = mean(distance..m. / 1000, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(runner_type = case_when(
    avg_distance_km > 13 ~ "Long-distance runner",
    avg_distance_km < 7 ~ "Short-distance runner",
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  ))

strava_filtered <- strava_runs %>%
  inner_join(runner_avg_distance, by = "athlete") %>%
  filter(!is.na(runner_type)) %>%
  mutate(
    distance_km = distance..m. / 1000,
    speed_m_s = distance..m. / .data[[time_col]]  # Use the identified time column
  )

ggplot(data = strava_filtered, 
       aes(x = distance_km, y = speed_m_s, color = runner_type)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 1.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Long-distance runner" = "forestgreen", 
                               "Short-distance runner" = "orange")) +
  labs(
    title = "Speed vs Distance for Long- and Short-Distance Runners",
    subtitle = "Grouped by runners' average distance: >13 km vs <7 km",
    x = "Distance (km)",
    y = "Run average speed (m/s)",
    color = "Runner Type"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 14),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12)
  )

#### Example of a good data visualisation

#{r ex4_good_viz, echo = FALSE, out.width = "80%"}
# edit the file path accordingly
knitr::include_graphics("img/population-with-un-projections.png")

Edit the text below by replacing the bold text with the appropriate information to provide a reference for your image (Please delete this message before submission!)

UN, World Population Prospects (2024) , https://ourworldindata.org/population-growth/ [Online]. Available at: https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/population-with-un-projections.csv?v=1&csvType=full&useColumnShortNames=true (Accessed: 31/10/2025)

The above image presents a good data visualisation because:

  • _Reason 1_Respects the Audience: The chart uses a clean, single line to make the complex trend of global population growth immediately understandable. Prominent labels (e.g., 10 billion) and a clear timeline allow anyone to grasp the scale and trajectory without technical expertise.
  • _Reason 2_Respects the Data and Context: It honestly communicates uncertainty by using a solid line for historical data and a dashed line for future UN projections. This clear visual distinction, supported by a source footnote, ensures the audience differentiates between measured facts and forecasted models.

Example of a bad data visualisation

Edit the text below by replacing the bold text with the appropriate information to provide a reference for your image (Please delete this message before submission!)

Emery, AnnK., Be Careful with the YAxis Depict Data Studio [Online]. Available at: ** https://depictdatastudio.com/be-careful-with-the-y-axis/ ** (Accessed: 31/10/2025)

The above image presents a bad data visualisation because:

  • _Reason 1_Disrespects the Audience: It presents raw numbers instead of a visual encoding like bars or a line, forcing viewers to mentally compare values (e.g., 26,113 vs.27,085) to see trends. This makes the data difficult and slow to understand.
  • _Reason 2_Disrespects the Platform: It misuses the graphical space. A charts purpose is to show relationships visually, but this design fails to transform the data into an intuitive visual form, making it an ineffective and inefficient chart.
